<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-485-217  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 485 217.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Sept 24 1990 v36 n1828 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Andersen protests CSC Treasury pact. (Andersen Consulting proteststhe US Treasury Department's award of the $48.4 million System 90contract to Computer Sciences Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Andersen Consulting files a protest with the General ServicesAdminstration Board of Contract Appeals over the TreasuryDepartment Financial Management Service's (FMS's) award of the$48.4 million System 90 contract to Computer Sciences Corp. System90 covers replacement and integration of hardware and software atthe Treasury Department's seven regional financial centers and theFMS National Computer Center.andP;  Andersen's protest claims thatComputer Sciences' price proposal was substantially lower than itsown and much lower than any reasonable estimate of the true costof meeting the System 90 requirements.andP;  Andersen claims FMS shouldhave assured that Computer Sciences' proposed price demonstratedan understanding of the contract requirements and reflected anability to perform the contract, as required by law.andP;  Andersenpresented several possible scenarios to explain Computer Sciences'low bid.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Sciences Corp. (contracts)Andersen Consulting (management).andO;Ticker:    CSC.andO;Topic:     Government ContractsCompetitive BiddingUpgradingInvestigationsComputer systems integrationUnited States. Department of the Treasury. Financial ManagementServiceUnited States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppeals.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>